          "body": "The first nine verses are the canon's only sustained royal instruction from a mother's mouth. She names the three appetites that destroy reigns: sexual indulgence (v. 3), intoxication (vv. 4-7), and judicial neglect (vv. 8-9). The first two are appetites *of* the king; the third is the appetite the king should *have* — a hunger for the *din* (legal cause) of the voiceless. Notice how the mother frames alcohol with theological precision: forbidden to rulers (because it makes them forget the decree and pervert justice) but commended for the dying and the bitter-souled (vv. 6-7). The Bible is not naïve about wine; it locates its proper and improper uses with surgical care. And the mother's climactic command — *open your mouth for the mute* (v. 8) — defines kingship: not as the consumption of privilege but as the deployment of voice on behalf of those who have none."
