          "body": "Verse 30 is the chapter's theological hinge: *charm is deceitful and beauty is vain (hevel — the same word that drives Ecclesiastes), but a woman who fears the LORD, she shall be praised.* The verse names the two measuring rods that compete for every life — external appeal vs. internal reverence — and decisively chooses the second. *Hevel* (vapor, breath, vanishing mist) is Ecclesiastes' verdict on everything under the sun; here it is applied to physical beauty. Beauty is real; it is also a vanishing thing. The fear of the LORD, by contrast, produces a life whose works praise it at the gates (v. 31) — public, durable recognition rooted in something that does not fade. The chapter that closes the book closes it where it opened: at the fear of the LORD (1:7)."
